The colorizer extension just uses regular expressions to parse strings/numbers/quotes/dates/etc... and uses the default styles from your selected VS Code theme and applies them.  

You can see the mapping of regex to the theme&#39;s css styles here:
https://github.com/IBM-Cloud/vscode-log-output-colorizer/blob/master/src/syntaxes/log.tmLanguage#L14

For example, dates will be given the `constant.numeric` style:

```
&lt;dict&gt;
	&lt;!-- Date MM/DD/(YY)YY --&gt;
	&lt;key&gt;match&lt;/key&gt;
	&lt;string&gt;\b(((0|1)?[0-9][1-2]?)|(Jan(uary)?|Feb(ruary)?|Mar(ch)?|Apr(il)?|May|Jun(e)?|Jul(y)?|Aug(ust)?|Sept(ember)?|Oct(ober)?|Nov(ember)?|Dec(ember)?))[/|\-|\.| ]([0-2]?[0-9]|[3][0-1])[/|\-|\.| ]((19|20)?[0-9]{2})\b&lt;/string&gt;
	&lt;key&gt;name&lt;/key&gt;
	&lt;string&gt;constant.numeric&lt;/string&gt;
&lt;/dict&gt;
```

Unfortunately, this extension does not allow you to specify your own styles or rules, but I&#39;ll keep that in mind as a new feature request.  

(I am the extension author).

